```suggestion
lemma memLp_tilted_mul (ht : t âˆˆ interior (integrableExpSet X Î¼)) (p : â„â‰¥0) :
```

```suggestion
  swap; Â· exact (memLp_tilted_mul ht 1).aestronglyMeasurable.aemeasurable
```

```suggestion
  rw [tilted_apply, mgf]
```
Do you think it's worth having a primed version for lemmas about `cgf` which assumes `NeZero Âµ` instead of `IsProbabilityMeasure Âµ`?

`exp_cgf_of_neZero` was strictly more general than `exp_cgf` so I removed the second one and renamed the first `exp_cgf` (with deprecation).
I added primed versions for cgf. The distinction is the same as for mgf: primed for measurable set without s-finite and non-primed for any set with s-finite.

```suggestion
  simp_rw [setIntegral_tilted_mul_mgf, exp_sub, exp_cgf ht]
```

```suggestion
  Â· simpa [hp] using hX.aestronglyMeasurable.mono_ac (tilted_absolutelyContinuous _ _)
```
This comment is true for all the primed statements. Should this rather be put in the module docstring? Or before all the primed versions? Or both?
I deleted it. The only reason it was there is that some of the code was written in a short window of time where a linter required a docstring on any primed lemma.

You shouldn't need `NeZero` here, because the result is obviously true for the zero measure. Something like
```
  rcases eq_zero_or_neZero Î¼ with rfl | hÎ¼ 
  Â· simp
  Â· simp_rw [tilted_mul_apply_mgf' hs, exp_sub, exp_cgf ht]
```
Same thing below.
I don't see how the lemma name corresponds to the statement. Maybe `setIntegral_tilted_mul_eq_mgf'`? (oterhwise, it seems to say you're multiplying the mgf by something). Same thing below.
